review_title: Perfect cover-up for the poop eating pup!
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on June 1, 2019
comment_content: My pup is one of those dogs who has the nasty habit of eating poop. If I don't monitor her then she will eat her own and  her sister's feces as well. Plus, both of my pups love to eat the cat and possum poop that gets burried under the mulch along the sidewalks late at night while the rest of the neighborhood sleeps soundly and unsuspectingly. My pups will yank me off course the second they smell the pungent poop de possum, burrying their noses in the dirt and slurping it up before I am able to react. DISGUSTING!!!!Lucky for me, awhile ago a friend accidentally had one of her orders from Chewy shipped to me. We got everything straightened out and sent her a new box, but I got to keep the box sent to me and I shared some of the goodies with a local rescue too. Anyways, among the goodies she had ordered were these Twistix Yogurt Chew Treats. She had ordered both the banana and mint flavors. I gave one to each of my sweet puppies, at a time when they were behaving, and I noticed how wonderful it made their breath smell. Surprisingly enough, my doggy doo doo eater normally has pretty good breath, however my other pup has pretty disgusting breath from licking her anal glands. Poop pup.Well, the next time Poopy Puppy managed to snag herself a disgusting snack I decided she needed to floss her teeth with a Twistix Yogurt and Banana Dental Chew treat. Boy am I glad I gave her one! It did the trick of cleaning out the nasty particles that I could see clinging to her back teeth when she had flashed me a big, toothy grin and I easily caught a waft of her sewage breath. But after the Twistix I wasn't as paranoid about her stealing one of my pillows off of the couch or doing something equally appalling.I know I chose to live with this disgusting monster, and I definitely love her. But I'm truly thankful to have discovered something that helps make the difficult parts much more bearable. Because it's no fun to think the best thing in your life is unbearable in the slightest.

review_title: I was worried about these treats when I first took them out of the bag because they're hard like chalk and my dog is 13 years ol
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on February 8, 2016
comment_content: My Yorkie loves these treats. I was worried about these treats when I first took them out of the bag because they're hard like chalk and my dog is 13 years old. She didn't like them right away but after she started to spend some time on them, they started to dissolve and she could chew on them more easily. These treats are great for distracting dogs but you also have to be careful if they're a smaller dog because the treat is really hard and I could see it could cause choking in over ambitious dogs that don't take the time to break down the treat. The only flaw in these treats is that my dog has a beard and these treats get really milky and foamy and once she finishes her treat it looks like she has rabies and that she's foaming at the mouth. I always find chunks of unfinished twistix dental chews melted to her beard with foam. She loves them so much and they're good for her teeth so I can't complain. I just have to clean her up every time after she's had one of these treats.

I'd definitely recommend these for any anxious dogs out there!

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 1, 2023
comment_content: My dogs loved these just as much as the popular brand of dog dental treats. They are much more firm by my feel, but they chewed them up fine. I have an Australian shepherd and a beagle. I was worried about the beagle swallowing it whole, but she chewed it well.I did not notice a difference in their energy levels- my Aussie is very energetic and my 13 year old Beagle has high anxiety. Maybe with more use I would notice a change.I'm not a fan of the smell, but it's not terrible. Just weird. Like perfumed beef jerky.

review_title: Healthy and my dogs love them
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 29, 2023
comment_content: These are great chews. The ingredients are natural and healthy, and my dogs really love them.Potatoes are the first ingredient, and there are a number of calming ingredients like chamomile, hops, passion flower, lemon balm, and lavender.They really do seem to calm my dogs down after around 20 minutes of chewing.  But I wish they told you the amount of active ingredients; you have no way of knowing the dosage of herbs in a product like this without that information.Still, the quality is very good and my dogs like them so I'm satisfied.Overall - good quality calming chews for dogs, but probably not the most effective calming treats out there.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 30, 2023
comment_content: We take our animals on vacation with us and we do all we can to make sure that they are safe and comfortable when we rent a house we will turn a room into an animal calm safe space to put them when we need to go out we know they are in a new environment and weirded out to be left alone so we want to make them as comfortable as possible. We bring their blankets white noise machines, all of their toys and their special treats that they only get on special occasions or traveling when we laughed and gave one of these to the dogs we let her start eating it before we left the house completely and she still had her eyes on us she looked like she was just really into the flavor. We laughed and went outside to peek through the window, just to see how it was since we finally left, she just seemed to calmly enjoy her treat , when we got home, she and the cat were both napping together it didn’t look like the cat had jumped around and disturbed too much or that the dog had really done anything either. It was very nice to come in to that pleasant relaxing site of them instead of seeing signs of distress and them scratching and whining at the door as soon as they heard us coming in

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 26, 2023
comment_content: I didn't notice a difference in behavior. As a dental chew, it only lasted maybe 30 seconds, but I have a very aggressive chewer. Overall, these didn't work as expected, but my dog still enjoyed them.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 9, 2023
comment_content: My dogs really like these dark colored chew sticks and will keep them busy for about 5 minutes.  These are supposedly chicken flavor and upon opening the bag, you get the scent of chicken bouillon and original Pringles potato chips.  I would surmise that they are definitely flavored like chicken and that my dogs seem to really like them.  The dark color of the sick does not seem to stain light carpet, but if you have a dog that likes to lick and moisten the treat before eating it then that may be a different story, however neither their teeth nor tongue were stained after eating these treats.  I can't say how well they clean teeth or freshen breath, but since the sticks are pleasantly scented, they don't seem to contribute to foul smelling breath.  These sticks are about the right size for small and medium sized dogs, however any size dog would probably like these treats.  If you are looking for a chew treat for your dog that actually has chicken scent, these are it.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 6, 2023

review_title: Great at getting our big baby to focus
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 12, 2021
comment_content: We have a 8 month old retriever who were training to be a hunting dog. Most of our program has trained with hot dogs, however carrying a pocket of hotdogs around isn't always feasible. review_date: Reviewed in the United States on October 12, 2021
comment_content: We don’t have a puppy, but these little chicken treats are ideal for our small, spoiled dog, who has put on weight over the years and doesn’t always need to have a larger, more extravagent type of treat. I think she likes the chicken flavor of these treats, and I like how they contain probiotics and colostrum for gut health and improved immunity.The list of ingredients in these treats is mercifully short, indicating there isn’t a lot of processed junk. review_title: one out of three cats will eat these but that is the one who I needed to and these have helped him
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 28, 2021
comment_content: So the 2 year old healthy cat won't touch these, the five year old fat cat ate these once then wouldn't eat them again.  The 4 month old stray we adopted over a month ago who is having a hard time kicking a pretty bad kitty herpes flare loves these and he is the one who I needed these for.  We have been giving him 500mg lysine twice a day as the vet directed and keeping him on antibiotics to prevent a bacterial side infection in his lungs, but he has not been getting any better.  Within two days of giving him these he has less rattling in his lungs, this has been the only improvement in his condition we have seen in over a month.  I did the math and for 6 chews there is only about 70mg of lysine, and since we have been giving him high doses of lysine for over a month the lysine is obviously not the ingredient in these chews that is helping.  I am therefore left to assume it is the probiotic.  While he is still far from recovered this has given me hope and I am going to look into a more broad spectrum probiotic and see if we can get him over this flare and onto a preventive regime which I think these chews will make be a part of.

review_title: My Cat Thumbs His Nose At This
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 28, 2021
comment_content: Every cat is an individual, and they know what they like and what they don't. Although many cats seem to love these Biteables, my senior cat would have nothing to do with it. I tried a single treat whole, then broken in half, and he just sniffed it and walked away each time. The next morning I even broke one in half and hid it in the middle of his wet cat food, which he normally inhales the minute I put it in his bowl. He ate around the treat halves and left them in his otherwise empty bowl. He loves chicken, which is the primary ingredient in these treats, but apparently that wasn't enough to entice him. In people years my cat is 88 years old, so it's not like he's going to change his food preferences at this stage of his life. The "chicken and tuna recipe" on the package is a bit misleading, since the tuna is only "natural tuna flavor" and not the real deal, and the same with the "natural fish flavor." I am still rating this product 3 stars even though my cat didn't like it because I think the L-lysine, taurine, and probiotics probably would have been good for him if he had been willing to eat these treats.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on October 24, 2021
comment_content: So I was really hoping our cats would love these soft treats so I could feel good about giving treats that had some health value to them. Unfortunately only 1 of our 3 cats would remotely touch them and it was only once.  I’m sure it’s just that our cats are picky about their food and treats.  They seems to be good quality with good packaging. Our cats just prefer the junky treats to the healthy ones. Go figure.

review_title: Both of my cats hate the flavor
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on October 30, 2021
comment_content: Different cats have different tastes so normally I wouldn't give a product two stars just because my cats didn't like the flavor but I really think it's warranted and possibly even generous in the case of Get Naked Essential Health Biteables because both of my cats really love treats but they absolutely hate these.The package boasts that Get Naked Biteables provide essential health benefits including lysine and probiotics and that the #1 ingredient is real chicken--although that last one doesn't actually mean anything because they could be saying that the highest quality or most expensive ingredient is chicken, not necessarily that chicken makes up the largest actual portion.  In any case, these are not cat food--they are cat treats.  With cat food, strong health benefits are definitely something you want to look for but with treats the number one most important thing is flavor.  Cats should be thrilled when you pull out the package and they see that you are about to give them a treat.I have two cats.  They both love treats.  They both ate exactly one of these Get Naked Bitables treats and will not touch them again.  They absolutely hate the flavor which means these aren't much of a treat as far as my cats are concerned.  Get Naked Biteables might well be very nutritious but they neglected the single most important thing that every cat treat needs which is great taste.

review_title: A treat that is more like a vitamin!
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on October 25, 2021
comment_content: Our Siamese kitten is kind of picky about her food yet she loved these soft heart shaped chewable cat treats. They are made in the USA, and chicken is the first ingredient, however they smell more fishlike.  These treats are more than a treat, they are a probiotic containing Lysine which is an essential amino acid helps pets produce antibodies and enzymes that support immune systems.  It is also helpful for calcium absorption which supports strong bones and promotes healthy skin. This is important, so our kitties can fight diseases and have healthy bones. Cats do not make lysine on their own. They must obtain it through their food and supplements.  L-lysine is not for all cats so check with your vet. I do not agree on the dosage. I think these treats should be used sparingly because it can interfere with other medications. The package is small but affordable. I’m feeding our 7 month old cat one a day to support a healthy gut and immune system.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on October 13, 2021
comment_content: My cats really like these.  As in gobbled them down before the dog realized they were getting treats.  I may have to replace the other lysine treats with these.  However, a serving size is something like 4 or 5 a day.  With the number of cats I have, they will go fast. The other lysine treats I use are one to two a day.  And they aren't as popular.  Though fortunately, the one cat that really needs them also likes them.  And price-wise, they are about the same.However, they do make a joint health treat that I may have to try for my cat with a damaged spine (before I owned him - got him that way from the vet where he was dropped off)  I've yet to find a treat/pill that he will take.

review_title: Combination of treat and treatment for my feline
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 9, 2021
comment_content: My older gray tabby has had feline herpesvirus since she was a young adult. Lysine can be a good thing to try to help these cats with their symptoms of sneezing and rasping. She loves these Biteables and seems to think they are a treat on par with Temptations, and that is in contrast to other lysine supplements she has quickly lost interest in.Cats with breathing difficulties sometimes also have trouble with their sense of smell, and I suspect the ingredients here such as natural fish and tuna flavors are strong enough (but pleasant to the human nose) to maintain their appeal to a congested kitty. The main ingredients here are chicken, glycerin, sweet potatoes, tapioca starch and L-lysine.These snacks also contains dried Bacillus fermentation product, designed to promulgate digestive health.The manufacturer recommends five to six of these soft treats per day. The treats are made in the US and specifics are not provided (that I can see) on where the ingredients are sourced.Review of Get Naked Essential Health Biteables, Land & Sea Recipe, 3 oz,Natural,912672

review_title: Caution; Throw Out When It Gets Hard!
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on April 14, 2021
comment_content: So, I've been getting these for my dog a while now. She normally scarfs them down over the course of an hour, but the latest time, she decided she wanted to keep one end of it to put in her little treat stash. About a week later, she grabbed it, we played fetch with it (it was hard like rock now) and she ate it; I thought nothing of it because it still chewed apart. Later that day, about 12 hours, she threw up a large amount pieces that weren't digesting. Even though they weren't splintering, the pieces were just sitting in her stomach like a bunch of rocks. They were getting smoother and I'm sure still digesting, but they were also causing obvious pain to her and she was unable to eat anything else while they were still clanking around in her stomach.I'd still absolutely recommend these to dog owners, but with much more caution and awareness. Once the texture isn't the soft-ish bendable feel it was out of the bag, its time to toss it. I got lucky she threw them up, and that none of the harder bits did splinter, but its important to be aware of things like intestinal blockages or damage that can occur from treats that appear fine.

Reviewed in the United States on October 29, 2022
comment_content: I have purchased these many times as my ferret loves their chicken flavor treats. Oddly though, the last time I purchased 2 bags of the chicken flavor ones they looked darker, almost black. My ferret would not eat them. I already purchased the bacon flavor for him awhile ago and he would not eat those either. In the provided picture, the first bag (left) are the chicken ones I am referring to that I just bought and he won't eat. The bag in the middle is my last "good" ones I bought and the last time they shipped the ones he loved. Note that these are way lighter in color than the ones on the left. The bag on the right are the bacon ones he won't eat. So, in conclusion, the chicken bag ones on the left look exactly like the bacon ones in the bag on the right. I think they may have put the bacon flavor ones in the chicken bags by mistake. Now I am afraid to order more as I can't be sure they will be correctly packaged and Amazon will not accept returns for them. If you know ferrets, they can be very fussy regarding food and treats so I hope someone that can do something to fix this problem will see this review!

review_title: Great treats for the little kitties!
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on July 29, 2023
comment_content: Our 12 week old kitten has been eating these for a few weeks now and as his Mom, I feel really good about the ingredients and good amounts of protein, fat, and moisture in them. He's not food motivated at all and has been super accepting of his diet that includes free feeding good quality kibble with canned offered instead a few days a week. He definitely loves and wants that canned food but even then, never really eats with gusto. I say all this to explain that he just doesn't get all that excited over any food, but he does enjoy these treats.They are rather large, at least 5x the size of a single piece of kitten kibble, but no problem, because breaking these treats up is easy and makes treat time last a little longer.I also worried that these treats would arrive all smashed and broken as some reviewers have experienced, but that wasn't the case here. Lots of soft little hearts that I can break up myself.I feel good that I'm offering a healthy, low calorie treat, and that that my silly, wild, non-food-motivated little guy likes them enough to pause his crazy play time for one of these.

review_title: I Buy this Over and Over
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on February 1, 2023
comment_content: I have had this on my Subscribe and Save for quite awule now. My dogs are not puppies, so I don't use these for "puppy teething". I give them pieces of these purely for healthy bedtime treats. I use kitchen shears to cut the rings into several pieces (each piece about an inch long).Then at bedtime, when my doggies are done eating for the day, they each get one piece. I feel the chewing motion helps clean their teeth and release healthy enzymes in their mouths. I love that the ingredients in these are so healthy and natural.And best of all my pups love their nighttime routine. They go out to potty, then race up on the porch and through the door to get their nightly pumpkin treats. Then time to snuggle with mommy & daddy!Oh, one more thing....once in awhile I get a bag where the rings are extra hard and brittle. When that happens, I just wet a clean paper towel, ring it out, then put it in the bag with the treats. I leave it sealed that way for about 24 hours. After that, they are more pliable and my kitchen shears cut through much better. And they are less brittle for my dogs' teeth that way too.

These help! The fact that they're curved into rings seems to really help her target whichever side of her mouth is hurting.That being said, these rings are HUGE. There are only 6 in a pack because they're so big, and the serving size starts at 1/4 a day?! So what, am I supposed to take the ring away after she's chewed through part of it? review_date: Reviewed in the United States on January 14, 2023
comment_content: I give my dogs a dental stick most every day, so we were happy to try out a bag of these dental rings.  The dogs really liked these and were able to devour them pretty quickly.  They did take slightly longer to chew than a normal dental stick, however.  The ingredients are not super alarming, though I don't think they are quite as good as our usual brand.  If you have a dog over 50 pounds, these are pretty easy to serve.  However, you are supposed to give dogs under 50 pounds less than a full ring a day, and these are rather hard to break.  You may be able to cut them, but I didn't think to try that because I have large dogs, so I am not sure how well that would work.  Each ring is 112 kcals, which is slightly more than the kind we usually use, so I like to give these only occasionally.  The bag does list all of the important information I look for; ingredients, guaranteed analysis, calorie content, feeding guidelines and expiration date. The dogs did not have any adverse reactions to these dental rings.  Though I don't feel this is the healthiest option out there, the dogs really loved them and the treats are not super unhealthy so I will probably keep these on as an occasional option to change up our daily routine.

comment_content: N-Bone Adult Dental Rings Chicken Flavor Dog Treats were a huge hit with my boys. I like the ingredients (mostly rice flour and gelatin, no weird ingredients), and they take a bit more time to chew than the usual dental chews I give them. Dogs do not care how their treats look!They're a bit big for my 20lb dog, although not if you ask him.  I was hoping I'd be able to break these rings in half, but they're way too hard to break. review_date: Reviewed in the United States on February 15, 2020
comment_content: Well you’re here reading so I guess you are. Six years ago I decided to adopt cat. I didn’t know which one yet just that I wanted a cat in my life. I went to a local shelter and found one that I liked a lot. When I talked to the clerk there she told me that the little guy I liked was really sick, and that their vet couldn’t figure out what was wrong with him. I got nervous about the costs associated with an undiagnosed illness, and when I made my thoughts known the clerk said “he’s not the cat for you.” I gave her this look of “excuse me?” And she continued saying, “when it’s your cat, you’ll know. And you won’t care what’s wrong or how much the medical bills might be, you’ll just know.” She suggested I go check out a couple other places and that if my heart was truly set on this little guy I could come back for him. Turns out she was right. He wasn’t the little guy for me, although I’m sure he found a very happy home. I went to another shelter that day and when I walked in, I turned to the cat room (it was very small and had no door) and started to go in. I remember the shelter was really loud. It was small so there wasn’t much of a barrier between the dogs and cats. But over all the chaotic noise I just heard this heartbreaking meow. I looked at the back of the room and there was this little grey floof meowing at the top of his lungs, standing up on his hind legs just staring at me. I immediately went over and got him out of the cage, and didn’t put him down again until we got home. I didn’t even ask if he’d had health issues, because that clerk was right. I didn’t care. Little did I know I chose a floof (named Jasper) that would end up with some serious health issues, costing around $6000 for the hospital stay and surgery, and expensive prescription food thereafter. Jasper had crystals in his bladder that he was unable to pass through his urethra. He almost died when it was at its worst, and even though it was suggested to me to put him down, I told the vet to try anything he could to save him. The surgery has a 50% success rate which is not great, but it was a success for Jasper. However, he now needs some special care to ensure he stays healthy. Although the prescription food helped immensely, I noticed he was still having digestive issues, and has had a couple of flare ups with his bladder. I tried so many different things but nothing really worked until I found these random cranberry treats on amazon. I figured, what the heck. Might as well. And they were a godsend. Not only is Jasper OBSESSED with these treats, but they help him so much! As long as I consistently give him these treats he doesn’t get bladder flare ups, and he throws up a lot less (now it’s just the occasional hairball for which I started using Loxatene). In general they just keep him much healthier and happier, and they’re ten times better than the royal canine prescription treats. A few months back they stopped selling these, and immediately Jasper started having some issues again. I’m so glad they’re back in stock, and I hope they stay that way. If your cat has urinary tract issues, I am begging you, try these! It is absolutely and by far the best product for kitty UT issues on the market. Quality ingredients, and proven to work. And for the record, I am not being paid or sponsored for this review. I just truly truly believe in this company and these treats after everything Jasper and I have been through. Anyway, if you’ve gotten this far, thanks for reading, and try the treats.

comment_content: I honestly can't rate these cat treats on how they affect a cats urinary health. My cat never had any urinary problems before eating these, and she has none now either. The treats themselves are crunchy, small and heart shaped. My cat doesn't love these (like she does some others... as she's "tempted" by another kind). She is though happy to have something different than just her regular food. These are well priced, although I'd like to make a suggestion to you all. I have purchased a bag of dry food, different than her regular, daily kibble (I bought it here, on Amazon). I use it as a "treat" for her, and whatever I give her, I subtract the same amount from her daily ration. This way, she thinks that she's getting her treats, but won't put on extra weight (which so many cats do, for this reason alone). It'll also save ALOT of money considering, for instance that a five pound bag of dry food would equal more than 20 bags of treats. Whoa, that's alot of money! My daughter turned me on to this idea, and I think she's pretty amazing for thinking of it. I wouldn't tell anyone not to buy these, especially if their cat does have urinary issues. But, I can't say that they would have any effect on it. Possibly checking with your cat's vet might be a good idea.

comment_content: My young male cat had blood in his urine, couldn't void completely, and had crystals. Honestly, I didn't think he'd make it. He's on the mend and is even playing with the other cats. However, if you're on the fence about these treats, it's true they are a love or hate thing. While the cat with urinary issues loves these, every other cat rejects them. I don't know whether there is something in them the one cat instinctively senses will help or he's just less picky. The recommended daily amount for a small cat is 5-6 per day (twice that for a large cat), so while the package is small, I think they will last a while. comment_content: I have a cat with FLUTD and have to keep him on special food to prevent crystals forming in his bladder. He's been to the emergency vet more times than I can count due to this issue. review_title: Made my ferret sick! Causes dramatic drop in blood sugar, diarrhea and vomiting in ferrets!
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 5, 2022
comment_content: My ferret started throwing up 30-45 min after eating 3 of these.  He was lethargic and it was a scary night.  After some research I found out that ferrets are not supposed to have sweet potatoes which is one of the main ingredients.  It can cause upset stomach and blood sugar issues.  I’d stay away from these treats.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on May 2, 2020
comment_content: My ferret is a finicky eater, and he really enjoys these treats!

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on February 10, 2022
comment_content: I bought these and didn't realize until after I bought them that they aren't safe for ferrets. They contain sweet potato as the second ingredient. Ferrets are obligate carnivores and cannot digest vegetables, starch, etc. They also contain vegetable glycerin (essentially sugar), and sugar has been shown to cause insulinoma and/or make it worse. Consider buying freeze-dried treats (there are some marketed for cats but only contain meat and are safe).

comment_content: My new Shih Tzu puppy loved them when i first started giving him these. He would mow them down like a wood chipper! Lol They are a bit small or skinny so good size for even teacup size dogs like even below 3lbs( had a Yorkie that was 2 1/2lbs, Hadley, before i got Viserys, my Shih Tzu)but I would suggest that you watch or moderately supervise your dog while he/she eats them. I have heard reports that some dogs have choked or got them stuck in their mouths and throats. So to be safe, make sure your dog is in eyes view of you while he treats himself to these. They are apparently tasty to them. I started giving him the peanut butter ones for a bit of variety and now he won’t eat any more of both flavors. Lol I may have just gave them to him a bit too much and he got tired of them too quickly but everything seemed fine before the peanut butter ones. Came to find out he had been hiding them away in the folds of his bed. I go to clean his bed out and i find all these sticks! He was eating them at first seemed to love them. Idk what the heck happened. Dogs are finicky.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on March 7, 2021
comment_content: These little chew bones are perfect for a tiny, teacup puppy.  The bones are soft enough to bend without breaking. We purchased them for our 4-lb puppy. So, we are cutting the treats in half and putting them outside for the squirrels, who might find them too small too. To be fair, there are a good amount of treats in the bag. review_title: Missnamed, but a good product for young puppies.
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on February 17, 2017
comment_content: I give one of these to my young puppy every night at bedtime.  Takes him just a couple of minutes to chew, but settles him right down and he knows it is part of the routine. I don't think they do much for satisfying the need to chew, as there are better options for that, but they are a nice treat.  There are puppy teething rings made by this same company which last a bit longer - but they also cost more and you don't get very many in a package.  I use those when I have them for the same purpose of settling my puppy down at bedtime, but they also don't do much to satisfy the need to chew, despite the name of the product.  I think these sticks (and the rings) are best for very young puppies, no more than five months.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on January 9, 2017
comment_content: I absolutely love these and so do the pups! Many people also use them as a treat as they do get eaten very quickly and some would argue that they do not help for teething. For a small breed dogs and young pups these do work great for teething. I gave them to the pups when they started getting teeth and they were unable to "eat" them yet but they loved the taste and it did help them with teething. Once they got older and were able to eat them it was more of a reward yes but it still helped with their back teeth which take the longest time to "pop out". The momma and daddy dogs even tried to steal them because they are so yummy! I also like these because they are edible and are much healthier to eat then raw hides. I recommended these to all of the new owners of our pups!

comment_content: This review is going to be a bit different... My cat loves these, I first bought them at a store and they were soft and she enjoyed teething on them. review_title: One of my cats favorite treats
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on February 14, 2024
comment_content: I wanted to find a soft treat for my cats that was healthy and had cranberry in it that my cats would both eat. That is tricky nowadays having two cats with different tastebuds. However ever since I’ve found this on a pet store shelf I will search until I can get my hands on it! I only can find it online now but it makes me feel better that my cats are getting a healthy treat in them that hopefully will help prevent issues down the line.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 19, 2021
comment_content: So, the super finicky felines that rule the house can, coincidentally, be super finicky about their treats. One will throw up if he gets more than 2-3 at one time, another looks at them and gives me a blank look as if asking “What did you just try to pawn off on me?”, and then there’s the third one that is all-the-treats-all-the-time. So I have a hard time finding treats that they will all like or at least two out of three. So what did they think of these?Smell (that’s mostly me): On the mild side. Didn’t really smell like chicken to me.Hard/soft: Very soft. Two of the cats seemed to eat them okay, but the one that’s missing most of her teeth had trouble with them.Taste (that’s them): they seemed a bit dubious and I think that might be down to the mild smell. While they did eat them, the toothless one was the slower of the three to jump on them.Overall: I like that this product is made in the USA and it’s for all life stages since ours range from 4-11yo. I’ve also found that they do seem to enjoy cranberry when it’s in their foods, which is always a bonus for me (and them). And at the listed price, it’s about on par with other similar products out there. In looking at the brand, I also see that there’s other flavor options, which I intend to investigate.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 20, 2021
comment_content: My cat loved these...once.  He then didn't want anything to do with them.  They really do smell awful, which may be a turn-on for some cats but for mine - not so much, I guess.

review_title: Cats liked them but they smell horrible
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 14, 2021
comment_content: My cats like these treats, but they smelled horrible.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 27, 2021
comment_content: We have six cats and Temptations are their kitty crack of choice, but these far-healthier Naked Biteables are beloved by Woodrow and Wolfie, brothers who are prone to minor but regular UTIs. These treats contain cranberry and that's exactly what they need in their diet to make sure they don't develop problems.While I do add a powder UTI supplement to their food at meals, I love that they come running for these treats several times a day as well. It helps keep them safe and happy.Not all of the other four like them but that's fine. The two that benefit most absolutely love them and I love giving them to them.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 22, 2021
comment_content: I have 3 cats who will eat ANY treat but these. They smell horrid and are very pricy!

user_name: A reader, a crafter, a gardener and cook
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 23, 2021
comment_content: Eight of my nine cats loved these. The ninth will eat one but if I put down more than one at a time she'll leave the others.They're a good size for cats. I have a tiny 6 lb one and a massive 16 lb one and they both can get these down.They're semi-moist, you can compress them and put a fingernail through them, not crunchy at all. But they aren't moist enough to form them around a pill like a Pill Pocket either.

review_title: They were great for a few days, but not anymore.
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 26, 2021
comment_content: Based on both cats loving the purple furball soft-treats made by the same company, I thought I'd give the health soft-treats a try. At first, both cats would devour them just like the other kind. However, after a few days, the pickier of the two would begin to vomit after eating a few of the health treats, and even the other one would no longer inhale them like he used to.2 days later, the fussy eater will not touch the health treats at all, and will also no longer touch the furball treats - shame, thought I'd finally found something she'd like, but I guess it was not meant to be. Might give it a few days and see if she wants to try at least the furball treats again, but it does look like the health treats are a lost cause for both cats.

review_title: Get Naked Biteables Natural Soft Treats
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 26, 2021
comment_content: Every night at bedtime my cat gets a treat. She demands treats because it’s our routine. She has a variety of different ones but I’ve been trying to introduce treats that also have some health benefits and am not having much luck. I gave her one of these treats with her regular nightly treat. That one piece has been sitting uneaten for three nights now. She eats her regular ones but is ignoring this one. If you’re cat will eat it, it’s a good option. But Darcy is not interested.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 6, 2021
comment_content: I ordered these for our 5 year old cat. I wouldn't consider him extra picky, but he defiantly was when it comes to these treats. I tried to offer them to him several times and every time he said nope. I then gave the bag to a friend to try and his cat also said no. I wouldn't buy these again, so I couldn't recommend them (even though we've had fantastic luck with all the other Get Naked products in the past).

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 25, 2021
comment_content: As soon as I opened the resealable pouch this product came in, my cat zeroed in on the relatively strong fragrance and frantically made his wishes known by rubbing and bumping my legs. Now the mere sight of the package elicits a "give me" response, and he seems to continue to enjoy it subsequently as much as originally with no obvious adverse allergic or digestive reaction.

review_title: 6lb 16 week mini schnauzer - loves it, lasts ~3 days
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on February 23, 2023
comment_content: We have a 16 week old mini schnauzer puppy who loves these things. Part of it is definitely that he can sink his teeth into it multiple times (kinda like a hard wax texture?), part of it is the shape due to how he tosses it, and another must be the flavor.  Thankfully it doesn't smell as bad as the bully stick nor the cod skins we have.  The cod skins do not offer the "teeth sinking" feeling this does, and while bully sticks do they stink so much.I would note that these rings do leave a sticky hard residue, likely from the rice flour or maybe the gelatin as it reminds me of how my hands feel after getting dried over cooked rice on clothing. His beard and paws feel crunchy afterwards and this can also end up on you, clothing, and furniture. We find this a very fair trade for the length of time this has entertained our landshark puppy though when compared to the smells of bully sticks and codskins (or the left over scales). Some hot water on a wash rag can clean it up easily without stains.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on October 19, 2022
comment_content: My maltipoo pup loves these. I had ordered the tiny dog size when she first started teething, then mistakenly ordered the regular sized ones during Amazon's Pet Days event. I made do by cutting those in half until we used them all up, but the tiny puppy ones are just the right size.When she was younger, a ring would keep her occupied for a good 30 mins or more. Now at eight months of age with all her permanent teeth either fully in or growing in, it takes her maybe 15 minutes to finish one off. Still a good busy-time treat while I'm on Zoom calls or as a reward for really good behavior, but I do wish they were a little bit longer lasting.These are also made in the U.S., which is important to me after so many imported pet treats have caused health issues. All in all, they're a bit pricey but worth it.

review_title: 6lb 16 week mini schnauzer - loves it, lasts ~3 days
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on February 23, 2023
comment_content: We have a 16 week old mini schnauzer puppy who loves these things. Part of it is definitely that he can sink his teeth into it multiple times (kinda like a hard wax texture?), part of it is the shape due to how he tosses it, and another must be the flavor.  Thankfully it doesn't smell as bad as the bully stick nor the cod skins we have.  The cod skins do not offer the "teeth sinking" feeling this does, and while bully sticks do they stink so much.I would note that these rings do leave a sticky hard residue, likely from the rice flour or maybe the gelatin as it reminds me of how my hands feel after getting dried over cooked rice on clothing. His beard and paws feel crunchy afterwards and this can also end up on you, clothing, and furniture. We find this a very fair trade for the length of time this has entertained our landshark puppy though when compared to the smells of bully sticks and codskins (or the left over scales). Some hot water on a wash rag can clean it up easily without stains.

review_title: My cat is addicted to these
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on August 17, 2020
comment_content: I have two cats. One of them played with these sticks for a little while but didn't seem to figure out they were chewable, even when I stuck them in his mouth. Oh well, he's a little dumb anyway.The other cat LOVES them. She needs her stick fix every day. She gets one at 6pm and the other around midnight, and she knows it - when the time comes she'll go to the kitchen counter and start meowing and begging for them. Sometimes she plays fetch with the stick, but most of the time we throw it for her, she runs after it, grabs it and starts chowing down. She even figured out how to stick one end into the high pile carpet so that she can keep it stable while she gnaws on the other end. They seem to be doing a good job of keeping my girl cat's teeth clean; we have to give dental treats and water additives for the other cat. We've been subscribed to these sticks for over a year now and she goes through about three packs a month.So your mileage may vary with these sticks. From my sample size of 2, there's a 50% chance of stick addiction and 50% chance that they'll totally flop. Even so, I have to give them 5 stars because of how much my girl loves them. If they ever discontinue these, I'm going to have a very unhappy cat on my hands.Oh, and the first few times you give these to your cat, keep a close eye on them. My cat has never choked in her 1 year plus of eating these every day, but she has taken bites that were too large and immediately vomited them up after - I guess the large chunks didn't sit well in her stomach. If you have a very small kitten, they may choke.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 7, 2023

review_title: I have a cat who loves to chew but..
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on September 26, 2023
comment_content: So my cat loves to chew on pens or anything in the shape, sp I thought these would be more appropriate for him. He chew through 2 sticks but the 3rd time I tried to give him one he turned away from it. I gave one to the dog to show him they're the same thing but time after time he still turned away from it.I do know cats don't normally find "chew" toys necessary since cats don't typically chew in the same way dogs do. So perhaps this bone broth stick is just too hard for cats in general. But i think tbr taste is fine bc other animals in the house see it as a treat. in the end I turned to just finding some some what mildly freezed dried meat treats for his chewy-like behavior.Dogs however love the bone broth stick. I gave the rest of the bag to a toy poodle owner and her 2 dogs loved them. So 3 stars for decent dog treats that has the word cat on the bag. I don't think it's a bad treat, just not for cats.

review_date: Reviewed in the United States on April 20, 2022
comment_content: When I first bought these my cat really wasn’t that interested, but she warmed up to these. This has been a lifesaver for me because my cat has a G.I. issue and I have realize that when she starts trying to chew everything in my home office while I’m working, that it’s because her tummy is aggravating her. I now leave the sticks in my desk and when she starts chewing on my artificial plants and papers and pens, I offer her a stick and she now comes running. The downside is that she can’t hold it on her own without me holding it. However, it absolutely does the trick  and stops her from Destroying my house and eating something that she is not supposed to eat. She’s also fine with just less than one stick per day.It’s surprisingly sit well on her stomach as well and that makes me happy, because there’s not a lot of treats out there that she can have with a diet that she’s on. I don’t think of these like a cat treat, but more of a chew therapy for a cat that needs to chew on some thing. Hope this helps people in similar situations. Best advice, offer it to your cat when you see them chewing because they are more likely to try it and once they try it they may like it more. Again I would not offer this as just an occasional every day treat, as there are probably better ones out there if your cat does not have stomach issues.

review_title: Cats LOVE these! Great for teething
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on December 7, 2019
comment_content: My cats LOVED these as soon as they smelled them! Fantastic idea for teething kittens. My kitten won't use any teething toys, but he loves these!I don't really understand how someone can complain about there being more wheat and corn than chicken in this. They are supposed to be hard to wear down. I can't see this being possible with chicken being the primary ingredient. The formulation is perfectly right for what the product actually IS. Your cat isn't going to sit there and eat the entire thing in one sitting, so I'm pretty sure a little more wheat and corn than chicken isn't going to kill them.If you don't like the idea of your cats chewing on anything that isn't pure meat, you're not going to find anything like this usable. If your cat is allergic, you already know they are because you'll have to purchase special food for them, as well. N.y cats eat natural food, where meat is the primary ingredient, and there's still some veggies and grains in there, because in general they are GOOD for them and make up part of a well balanced diet.If your cat has allergies, though, you'll be happy to know there are catnip sticks on Amazon, too, which are literally sticks that have been broken off from the plant. Problem solved.This product though doesn't deserve the bashing another reviewer here gave it. My cats love it, they love their food too for that matter (they were the ones that picked it), and they're healthy. That's all I can really ask for.

review_title: Cat doesn't absolutely love them, but they sure do work.
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on April 11, 2016
comment_content: My cat isn't totally wild about them, but he does eat them. Sometimes I have to play with him a bit to get him to eat them. That is the only reason they are four stars instead of five. However, they work as advertised as dental treats. My little guy had tartar issues that led to bad breath and having two of his teeth pulled (not the fangs, thank goodness). Talked to the vet about how to improve, and she suggested chew treats. I had already tried Greenies, but my greedy cat gobbled them whole without chewing them. Definitely needed something in stick form that he would have to pull apart. Stumbled across these on Amazon and they work great. No more bad breath, and more importantly, no more dental issues. He gets a clean bill every checkup! He is actually scheduled to have his teeth cleaned once a year, but the vet recommended skipping the last time because his teeth were in such great shape. Worth the effort to get him to eat one every day!

review_title: Too dry? Wrap in moistened paper towel and refrigerate for 24 hours. Solution to Cats that obsessively chew on non food items!
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on January 20, 2018
comment_content: "Solution to My cat obsessively chewing on non food items like:  Power Cords, String, Yarn, Hair, Hair Ties, Rubberbands, Blind Cords, Twist Ties, Shoe Strings, Pens, Pencils, Thread, Dental Floss, etc....  He even chewed up and swallowed  a soft rubber-like small ball.  This is a condition cats get from being taken away from their mother too soon.  Keep close tabs on string like objects, Coat all power cords with "Bitter Apple Spray", and give him a N-Bone Cat Chew Treat!  Your cat doesn't like them? Try dipping it in butter.  Try holding it for him while he chews it up.  The cat chews are meant to be pliable.  Too dry?  Just wrap in a moistened paper towel and keep in the fridge for 24 hours.  They soften right up.  My cat goes on the hunt for something to chew on.  He sniffs the power cord smelling for one that is not sprayed with bitter apple.  This is when I give him a a N-bone Cat Treat and spray or respray the power cords!  It also helps to play with your cat daily!

review_title: Hit with our teething (potentially pica syndrome) kittens!
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on June 15, 2021
comment_content: One of my kittens seems to eat through everything (toys, random non-toy items, strings, wires, balls, etc.) and he's also teething; he may have pica. I've tried silvervine sticks, these N-Bone chew treats, and other natural chew-friendly cat toys made of silvervine, but he absolutely loves this treat! I give it to him once a day (or when I remember) and it seems to help with his urge to eat through things. It's a hit with our kittens, but we did have to teach them that it was ok to chew. comment_content: My cat is a 1 year old Turkish Van who is a big chewer. The packaging makes it look like it's a meaty chew, but its actually a firm clear-ish gelatinous stick, I'm assuming its a juice or or artificial flavoring? I won't be buying these again, but I'm glad this is on the market because I'm sure some cats would love it, just not mine. It's well packaged and is resealable. I'd like to suggest an alternative that I found that my cat actually likes. It's Dogswell Happy Hips Salmon or Chicken Jerky. They're made for dogs but they're just dehydrated meat with no hormones or additives so it's good for cats too, and your cat may like it if it doesn't like these because it's actually meat!

review_title: Cinnamon Chewy Goodness for Canine Teeth
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on March 24, 2014
comment_content: Living with a four dog pack as I do, daily brushing can become routine and cumbersome (I do it in the pm with Virbac Vanilla Mint enzymatic toothpaste which they love and which actually contributes to teeth health whether you brush or just swipe it through on a swab - enzymatic, so if you are introducing the idea or have a non cooperative dog it might be a good thing to check out as well for those reasons) so I look for fun ways to add to the process of canine teeth cleaning. I read an article somewhere about this product that made me look into it further. Note here, I am all about natural raw feeding, integrative vet care, wholesome ingredients and positive training and keeping up with new ideas like Reiki for animals. (It really works!).I bought the small chews for my standard size dogs (50 - 70 pounds) because I don't give large treats but prefer to parcel them out. Perfect size. After their breakfast they each get a chew stick and they love them. I feed them in their crates and the floor gets a bit slimy because they break off bits and shove them around but with crate feeding (the rare times the dogs use the crates anymore) the floors get cleaned up anyway. You can smell the cinnamon which I know is good for breath and other ailments in humans as well. One of my concerns with these dental type chews in the past has been the possibility of blockages and these appear to not pose that risk to my dogs, being narrow and chewy and not overly hard with ridges, kind of like a star shaped stick. I only give one a day per dog in the morning because I don't want to upset tummies and I want to keep these a special treat even though these treats have a job. I broke one into fourths and gave them to a friend with a Shi Tzu and suggested one piece per day for him since he is tiny. He loved them. So a little goes a long way. Between the Naked Chew in the morning and the Virbac Enzymatic toothpaste in the evening my dogs teeth are really improving and they are all seniors who had some residue I was looking to improve upon. Teeth are looking shiny white like me after a trip to my favorite dental hygienist. I recommend the combination. The raw diet does contribute of course. These are a safer, healthier dental chew than anything else I've seen with ingredients I am comfortable with offering my dogs in reasonable portions. I recommend supervising your dog at first and considering the size of your dog and the size of the treat and perhaps breaking the treat into smaller portions if you have a smaller dog and offering that either two a day or depending on the sensitivity of your dog's digestion. I order in quantity to reduce cost. I think this is a great product.

comment_content: I tried these for my rescue pup that has a very sensitive stomach and digestive issues and I'm so glad I did! He is about 55 pounds and does go through one rather quickly. But he hasn't had an issue at all with them affecting his stomach (which is AMAZING!) review_date: Reviewed in the United States on March 4, 2022
comment_content: I give this treat to my two kittens daily.  My one kitten is an avid groomer, she started trying to cough up hairballs a few days a week. I started giving one treat at a time to her during different times of the day.  Now she will eat all 3 at once.  The treats look soft, but they are a little hard. I also like the more natural ingredients along with the probiotics.  I will keep giving this to them as long as they like it.

review_title: Smaller and softer treats for smaller/older dogs
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on September 25, 2021
comment_content: We got these because our 15 year old chihuahua is very healthy for her age, but not able to eat anything hard because of some dental issues.We figured if she can get these down, they help her nutritionally, and make her happy, that would be a huge win.Regarding how she took to them...At first, she didn't eat these treats at all, but she is very fussy about food in general.Leaving a few near her favorite sleeping spot, she eventually decided she could deign to eat them as a snack.If you have a dog who is very into treats, I suspect they will gobble these up without hesitation.The treats themselves are: covered with some sort of yellow powder; they are quite small; their texture is soft, but not squishy, and though they have a scent, it is neither intense, nor unpleasant.As shown on the product page, the recommended serving is 8 to 10 treats for dogs 5 lbs and up.Whet they arrived, the treats had a best by date just over six months away, so they're not a treat you can keep on a back shelf forever.One thing I did not like is that they do not specify where these are produced.The company that sells them is based in Texas, but they do not state whether they are manufactured there, which leaves me wondering where they actually come from.Our picky lady does not eat these until she feels like it, but can manage them, even with some dental issues, so I think they are a good choice for senior dogs.She also has experienced no negative side effects from taking them, so that is obviously a big plus in and of itself.I would say if you are looking for a treat for an older dog that is small and easy for them to get down, this would be a good one to try.

review_title: Slightly different than the old formula....
review_date: Reviewed in the United States on November 29, 2016
comment_content: My three dogs have been big fans of the old formula of these treats for quite a few years now. They are special favorites of my oldest dog (12) and pickiest eater. Because he is still extremely active, I try to give him as much glucosamine and chondroitin as I can. So the Get Naked Joint Health treats were a wonderful discovery. My dogs also enjoyed the other flavors in the line.When the formula was discontinued with the launch of the new grain free version, I was incredibly disappointed. Especially because the new treats had not reached the super-affordable price I was used to with the old formula (< $4) and the price on the discontinued formula was skyrocketing, which is typical of a market for a discontinued product. I was afraid that my dogs wouldn't like the new formula or that it would make them sick. I still don't understand why they needed to go grain free, considering that the grains in the old formula consisted only of rice and oats (which I didn't think were a big concern in doggie diets), but I am very glad the treats came back down to the extremely affordable price that my dogs and I love. Happily, the treats pass the doggie taste test and have yet to come back up the way they came.So without further ado, here is my comparison to the old formula for the treats:OUTSIDE: To start of, the packaging of the treats is very similar in wording and warnings, although the ingredient list does differ a bit. The package is orange instead of chartreuse, and since I don't particularly like either color it doesn't matter much that the bag got uglier. However, the development of the new packaging was clearly misguided. Perhaps in an attempt to make the packaging look like more "natural" products do in most marketing, the appearance of the bag has been ~softened~ to the point where things are very hard to read. Ditching the outline on the letters on the front was a big mistake with the gradient to light orange in the center, since it makes the letters look so fuzzy I thought my glasses were dirty or falling off my face. On the back, the crisp black lettering for the nutritional information was traded in for an even smaller font in white letters again. I can see that the smaller font was likely necessary because the packaging is now bilingual in English and French, but the choice of white is once again irritating to the eye. Even the NPIC logo and company information is so blurry that it is completely illegible.INSIDE: The grain ingredients, as well as tapioca starch, in the old formula have been replaced with potatoes. The rest of the ingredients listed are the same. The nutritional analysis is almost identical, with the exception that the Crude Protein minimum is 20% instead of 18%. The glucosamine per serving (32mg) and chondroitin sulfate (19mg) are the same, and now DHA is listed as well (4mg). The calorie content per treat remains at 26 kcal.The treats themselves are the same length and shape as the old formula, and have an almost identical amount of give as far as the hardness of the treat goes (which is good because the 10 year old rescue dog only has 5 teeth). They are not scary hard, but chewy enough to keep the dogs entertained for a few minutes and delicious enough to get the dogs excited when they see their favorite treat bag (which they know by shape and sound). Watching my dog chomp away, I would say that these new treats may be a bit tougher to bit through, although not too much.I was a little disappointed when I compared the new and old treats and found that the new ones are a bit slimmer than they used to be. It's not much, but considering that there were 2 less in the bag than you got in the old formula that was a bit sad. However, I noticed that the new treats are slightly heavier per piece, and the higher density makes sense with the extra chewing my toothless wonderdog was doing. The smell of the new formula is comparable to the old, slightly different but similar and nothing my dogs minded too much.If the treats continue to stay at this low price, I'll be very happy and hopefully my concerns over the formula switch will have been for nothing. I don't think I would pay more than $5 or so per bag, but that's partly because I can't afford much more right now as a pet indulgence and partly because I'm also just cheap (as much as I can be while still taking great care of my dogs). Also, I prefer to give the two older dogs at least one of these per day, since it makes them happy and gives them some extra vitamins that their little arthritic knees crave. At this price, I can do that.[...] I rely on reviews for my online purchases and want to do my part by making my reviews as helpful as I can. Thanks for reading!
